## How to Use This Cookbook

This is a starter set. Each recipe is one pass through the Kitchen, Steps 1 through 9 of the Slow AI Kitchen method, for work a single professional or a small team can run without an org chart. It stays in Tier 1 and Tier 2. For high-stakes work, organizational deployment and sustained programs, the Feast and the Restaurant addendum in the method govern instead.

Every recipe uses the same eight fields. The order is the discipline. AI does not enter until field five. By the time you bring it in, you have already framed the task, defined done, completed the manual first pass and read the context. The AI extends a judgment you have already formed. It does not form one for you.

**Read a recipe top to bottom. If you reach for AI before field five, you are cooking the wrong way.**

Recipes name capabilities, not models. A recipe that needs long context or file upload says so. It never names a product, because the model is interchangeable and the discipline is not.

Each recipe carries a tier. Tier 1 is low-stakes work where a quick human check is enough. Tier 2 is work that informs a real decision or leaves the team, so it needs a named reviewer and an evidence note. The tier on the card is a floor, not a ceiling. If a task starts to carry consequences beyond its tier, stop and run the full method.

**The card**

1. The Dish. What you are making, for whom, and the decision it supports.
2. Done Means. Three to five pass/fail checks, written before you touch AI.
3. Prep by Hand. The first pass you do yourself. No AI yet.
4. Watch For. Where this goes wrong and who is affected if it does.
5. Bring in AI. What to use it for, and what to never hand it.
6. Who Signs. The named human who owns the output.
7. Plate and Taste. Build to Done Means, then test against it.
8. Serve. Release within scope. One line on what you would change next time.

